An Overview of Screen Reader Software

01
On this page
  1. VoiceOver on Mac

NVDA & JAWS are popular Assistive Technologies for Windows users.

I recommend NVDA, as its license is free and the software is open source with an issue tracker on GitHub.

I highly suggest making NVDA testing part of your regular process, as there are times when VoiceOver on a Mac might work as expected but NVDA won't. This is often because Windows screen readers have different interaction modes than VoiceOver does.

Using virtual machine software like Parallels can make testing seamless on a Mac. I personally use a Windows hardware keyboard to make testing with screen readers easier (Macs don’t have an Insert key), but you can still make it work with a Mac keyboard. You can also remap keys using software solutions, such as mapping Caps Lock for Insert.

NVDA has an Elements List that's similar to the VoiceOver rotor, as well as a Speech Viewer option to show visual output similar to VoiceOver.

VoiceOver on Mac

VoiceOver works best with Safari on a Mac and that's how we'll start our testing.

Keep in mind that there are other screen readers that have higher usage, such as JAWS or NVDA for Windows. For day-to-day development on a Mac, testing with VoiceOver and Safari is a good start to becoming familiar with screen readers and the state of your application.
